window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>1>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : ALGEBRAIC FRACTIONS","question":"Simplify:42/9 - 113/15  21/5 + 4/7 \u00d7 21/3  (Leaving the answer in fracion a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Simplify:42/9 - 113/15  21/5 + 4/7 \u00d7 21/3  =(389-2815)\u2192Numerator  =570-252135=318135=10645  =21645    Denominator215+(47\u00d773)  =215+43  =115+43  =33 + 2015=5315  \u2234NumeratorDenominator=10645\u00f75315  =10645\u00d71553=2\u00d713=23","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>1>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SURDS (RADICALS)","question":"By rationalizing the denominator, simplify : 7&radic;5&nbsp; &radic;7&nbsp;  (leave your answer in surd form hint &radic;ab&nbsp;)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Rationalizingbysimplifying:7&radic;5&nbsp;&radic;7&nbsp;  Rationalizing=7&radic;5&nbsp;&radic;7&nbsp;\u00d7&radic;7&nbsp;&radic;7&nbsp;=7&radic;35&nbsp;7= &radic;35&nbsp;","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>2>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : PROFIT AND LOSS","question":"A dealer sold a car to a man and made a profit of 15%. The man then sold it to a woman for \u20a6120,175.00 at a loss of 5%. How much did the dealer buy the car?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The man sold the car for \u20a6120,175.00 at a loss of 5%  Thecostpriceofthecartotheman=105100\u00d7120175  = \u20a6126,183.75  The dealer sold the car for \u20a6126,183.75 at a profit of 15%. Then, the actual cost price of the car to the dealer.  =\u20a6(100115\u00d7126,183.75)=\u20a6109,725=\u20a6110,000.00","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>2>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : LENGTHS AND PERIMETERS","question":"The diameter of the wheel of a car is 36cm. How many revolutions, correct to three significant figures, will it make to cover a distance of 1.05km?  (Take \u03c0 = 22/7)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Diameter of wheel of a car = 36cm  Circumference,C=\u03c0d=227\u00d736  \u22341revolution=7927cm  the distance covered = 1.05km  The distance covered = 1.05km = (1.05 \u00d7 1000 \u00d7 100)cm = 105,000cm  Numberofrevolutions=105,000\u00d77792=928.0303=928rev.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>3>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : SIMULTANEOUS LINEAR EQUATIONS IN TWO VARIABLES","question":"Solve for x and y in the following equations:  2x - y = 9/2; x + 4y = 0","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Solving for x and y  2x - y = 4.5 ...... (1)  x + 4y = 0 ......(2)  from (2) let x = -4y  2(-4y) - y = 4.5  -8y - y = 4.5  -9y = 4.5  y=-12  substitute for y = -1/2 in (1)  2x - ( -1/2 ) = 4.5  2x+12=4.5  2x = 4.0  x = 2","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>3>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram, TA is a tangent to the circle at A. If \u2220BCA = 40\u00b0 and \u2220DAT = 52\u00b0, find \u2220BAD.    (Leaving the answer in whole number ab)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given, TA is a tangent \u2220BCA = 40\u00b0 and \u2220DAT = 52\u00b0  \u2220DAT = AC\u0302D = 52\u00b0   (angles on alternate segment)  The opposite angles of a cyclic quadrilateral are supplementary.  \u2220BCD + \u2220BAD = 180\u00b0  Where \u2220BCD = 40\u00b0 + 52\u00b0 = 92\u00b0  \u2234 92 + \u2220BAD = 180\u00b0  \u2220BAd = 180\u00b0 - 92\u00b0 = 88\u00b0","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>4>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SETS","question":"In a class of 45 students, 32 offered Physics (P), 28 offered Government (G) and 12 did not Offer any two subjects.  Draw the Venn diagram to represent the information.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>4>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : LOGICAL REASONING","question":"In a class of 45 students, 32 offered Physics (P), 28 offered Government (G) and 12 did not Offer any two subjects.  How many students offered both Physics and Government?  (Leaving the answer in whole number ab)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"P and G = x  45 = (32 - x) + x + (28 - x) + 12  45 = 32 + 28 - x + 12  45 = 72 - x  45 - 72 = -x  -27 = -x  x = 27","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>4>a>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"In a class of 45 students, 32 offered Physics (P), 28 offered Government (G) and 12 did not Offer any two subjects.  What is n(P \u222a G)?    (Leaving the answer in whole number ab)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"n(P \u222a G) = n(P) + n(G) + n(P \u2229 G)   = 32 - x + 28 - x + x   = 60 - x   = 60 - 27 = 33","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>4>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : ALGEBRAIC FRACTIONS","question":"Ifp=2u1-uandq=1 + u1 - u,expressp + qp - qintermsofu.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"p=2u1-uandq=1+u1-u,expressingp+qp-qinu  p+q=2u1-u+1+u1-u=2u+1+u1-u=3u+11-u  p-q=2u1-u-1+u1-u=2u-(1+u)1-u=2u-1-u1-u=u-11-u  \u2234p+qp-q=3u+11-u\u00d71-uu-1=3u+1u-1","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>5>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"Two fair dice are tossed together once.  Draw the sample space for the possible outcomes.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Two fair dice sample space    1  2  3  4  5  61  1, 1  2, 1  3, 1  4, 1  5, 1  6, 12  1, 2  2, 2  3, 2  4, 2  5, 2  6, 23  1, 3  2, 3  3, 3  4, 3  5, 3  6, 34  1, 4  2, 4  3, 4  4, 4  5, 4  6, 45  1, 5  2, 5  3, 5  4, 5  5, 5  6, 56  1, 6  2, 6  3, 6  4, 6  5, 6  6, 6","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>5>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"Two fair dice are tossed together once.  Find the probability of getting a total of 7 or 8.    (Leaving the answer in fraction a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Probabilityof(gettingatotalof7)=636=16  Probabilityof(gettingatotalof8)=536  \u2234Theprobability(gettingatotalof7or8)=636+536=1136","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION I>5>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"Two fair dice are tossed together once.  Find the probability of getting a total less than 4.    (Leaving the answer in fraction a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The probability (getting a total less than 4)  =336=112","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>6>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : AREAS","question":"A sector of a circle of radius 8cm subtends an angle 90\u00b0 at the centre of the circle. If the sector is folded without overlap to form the curved surface of a cone. Find  the base radius    (Leaving the answer in whole number format a)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Length of arc (sector) = circumference of cone  (\u03b8360\u00d72\u03c0r)sector=(2\u03c0r)cone  90360\u00d72\u03c0\u00d78=2\u03c0r  14\u00d78=r  r = 2cm  \u2234 radius, cone = 2cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>6>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"A sector of a circle of radius 8cm subtends an angle 90\u00b0 at the centre of the circle. If the sector is folded without overlap to form the curved surface of a cone. Find the height    (Leaving the answer in two decimal places a.cb)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Using Pythagoras theorem:  h2 = l2 - r2   = 82 - 22 = 64 - 4 = 60cm  h2 = 60cm  h = &radic;60&nbsp; = &radic;4&nbsp; \u00d7 &radic;15&nbsp; = 2&radic;15&nbsp;cm = 7.75cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>6>a>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"A sector of a circle of radius 8cm subtends an angle 90\u00b0 at the centre of the circle. If the sector is folded without overlap to form the curved surface of a cone. Find the volume of the cone.    (Leaving the answer in two decimal places a.cb)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Volume(cone)=13basearea\u00d7heigh=13\u00d7\u03c0r2\u00d7h  =(13\u00d7227\u00d74\u00d77.75)cm3=32.459cm3  \u2234 Volume of cone = 32.46cm3","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>6>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : LENGTHS AND PERIMETERS","question":"A map is drawn to a scale of 1:20,00. Use it to calculate the distance in kilometres, represented by 4.5cm on the map.    (Leaving the answer in one decimal places a.b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"4.5\u00d720,000100,000=4.55=0.9km","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>6>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"MENSURATION : LENGTHS AND PERIMETERS","question":"A map is drawn to a scale of 1:20,00. Use it to calculate the distance in metres, on the map, between two towns 16km apart.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"1m ------ 20,000  since 16km = 16000m  16000m ----- x  x = 20,000 \u00d7 16 \u00d7 103 = 32 \u00d7 106km","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>6>b>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : AREAS","question":"A map is drawn to a scale of 1:20,00. Use it to calculate the area on the map, of a forest, which covers 85km2.    (Leaving the answer in whole number format abcd)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Areaonthemap=85\u00d7(103)2cm2400,000,000=2,125cm2","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>7>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : LINEAR INEQUALITIES","question":"If 4x","images":[],"marking_scheme":"4x  4x - 3x  x  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp x > -4  The range of values of x = {-3, -1, 0 and 1}  To combine two inequalities; we have: -4","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>7>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : NUMBER BASES","question":"Represent your result in (i) on the number line.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>7>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : FINANCIAL ARITHMETIC","question":"A shop is sending out a bill for an amount less than \u00a3100. The accountant interchanges the two digits and so overcharges the customer by \u00a345. Given that the sum of the two digits is 9, find how much the bill should be.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let the original digits be xy, where the tens digit is x and the unit digit is y  - The sum of the digit = 9  x + y = 9 ......(1)  - The two-digit number is 10x + y  The customer overchanged by E = 45  \u2234 10y + x - (10x + y) = 45  10y + x - 10x - y = 45  9y - 9x = 45 (Divide through by 9)  y - x = 5 ......(2)  Solving simultaneously, Add (1) + (2)   x + y = 9  -x + y = 5  2y = 14  y = 7  substitute for y = 7 in (1)  x + 7 = 9  \u2234 x = 2  \u2234 The original bill xy is \u00a327","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>8","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"8","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : AREAS","question":"In the diagram, ABCBEO is two-thirds of a circle O. The radius AO is 7cm and |AB| = |BC| = |CD| = |DE|. Calculate, correct to the nearest whole numbers, the area of the shaded portion. (Take \u03c0 = 22/7).    (Leaving the answer in whole number format ab)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Area of the shaded portion = Total area of sector - Total area of \u0394s  *Totalareaofsector=4(\u03b8360\u00d7\u03c0r2)=4(60360\u00d7227\u00d77\u00d71)cm2=4(16\u00d7154)cm2= 102.666cm2  *Totalareaoftriangle=4(12absin\u03b8)  =4(12\u00d77\u00d77\u00d7sin60\u00b0)  =4(12\u00d749\u00d7&radic;3&nbsp;2)= 49&radic;3&nbsp; = 84.8705cm2  \u2234 Area of shaded portion (segments) = 102.666 - 84.8705 = 17.795= 18cm2 (nearest whole number).","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>9>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"Using a ruler and a pair of compasses only. Construct \u0394XYZ such that |XY| = 8cm and \u2220YXZ and \u2220ZYX = 45\u00b0.    (Leaving the answer in whole number format ab)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Bisect the angle at z or bisect |XY|","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>9>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"Using a ruler and a pair of compasses only. Locate a point P inside the triangle equidistant from YX and YZ.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Locate a suitable radius along the locus","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>9>a>iii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"Using a ruler and a pair of compasses only. Construct a circle touching the three sides of the triangle.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Draw a circle touching the three ides of \u0394","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>9>a>iv","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"Using a ruler and a pair of compasses only. Measure the radius of the circle.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Measure the radius","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>9>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : LINEAR EQUATIONS IN ONE VARIABLE","question":"The length of the sides of a hexagon are x - 5, 2x, 2x, 2x + 7, 2x and 2x - 1. If the perimeter is 144cm, find the value of x.    (Leaving the answer in whole number format ab)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Hexagon is a six-side shape, the length are given as:  x - 5, 2x, 2x, 2x + 7, 2x and 2x - 1  Perimeter = x - 5 + 2x + 2x + 2x + 7 + 2x + 2x - 1  144 = 11x + 1  144 = 11x + 1  11x = 143  x=14311=13","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>10>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The following table shows the distribution of test scores in a class.  Scores1234578910No of pupils1153k2 + 16234  If the mean score of the class is 6, find the value of k    (Leaving the answer in whole number format b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Score (x)No of pupil (f)f(x)1  2  3  4  5  7  81  1  5  3  k2 + 1 = 5  6  21  2  15  12  5(k2 + 1)  42  169  103   427  40Totalk2 + 265k2 + 160    Mean=\u2211fx\u2211f;  Mean = 6  \u22346=5k2 + 160k2 + 26  6(k2 + 26) = 5(k2 + 32)  6k2 + 156 = 5k2 + 160  k2 = 4  k = 2","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>10>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The following table shows the distribution of test scores in a class.  Scores1234578910No of pupils1153k2 + 16234  If the mean score of the class is 6, find the median score.    (Leaving the answer in whole number format b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Since; k = 2, the number of pupils = 22 + 26 = 30  Themedian=5 + 72=122=6","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>10>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"Draw a bar chart for the distribution.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>10>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"If a pupil is picked at random from the class, what is the probability that he/she will score less than 6?    (Leaving the answer in fraction a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The probability (that pupils score less than 6)  =k2 + 1 + 3 + 5 + 1 + 130;sincek=2  =22+1+3+5+1+130=1530=12","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>11>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"The diagram shows a pyramid standing on a cuboid. The dimensions of the cuboid are 4m by 3m by 2m and the slant edge of the pyramid is 5m. Calculate the volume of the shape.    (Leaving the answer in one decimal place ab.c)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From \u0394BGF  |BF|2 = |BG|2 + |GF|2   Pythagoras theorem  |BF|2 = 42 + 32  |BF|2 = 16 + 9  |BF|2 = 25  BF = 5m  From \u0394VXF  |XV|2 = |VF|2 - |XF|2  h2=52-(52)2  h2=25-254  h2=754  h=&radic;754&nbsp;=5&radic;3&nbsp;2=2.5&radic;3&nbsp;=4.33m  Volume of shape = volume of cuboid + volume of pyramid  Volume of cuboid = L \u00d7 B \u00d7 H = 4m \u00d7 3m \u00d7 2m = 24m3  Volumeofpyramid=13\u00d7Basearea\u00d7Height=13\u00d74\u00d73\u00d74.33=17.32m3  \u2234 Volume of the shape = 24m3 + 17.32m3 = 41.32m3","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>11>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SEQUENCE AND SERIES","question":"The 2nd, 3rd and 4th terms of an AP are x - 2, 5 and x + 2 respectively. Calculate the value of x.    (Leaving the answer in whole number format b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The 2nd, 3rd and 4th terms of an A.P are given as   (x - 2), 5 and (x + 2) respectively.  Let T1 = x - 2, T2 = 5, T3 = x + 2  T2 - T1 = T3 - T2  5 - (x - 2) = (x + 2) - (5)  5 - x + 2 = x + 2 - 5  7 - x = x - 3  -2x = -10  x = 5","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>12>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : GRAPHS OF SINE AND COSINE","question":"Copy and complete the table of the relation y - 2sinx - cos 2x  x0\u00b030\u00b060\u00b090\u00b0120\u00b0150\u00b0180\u00b0y0.5-1.0  Using a scale of 2cm to 30\u00b0 on the x-axis and 2cm to 0.5 unit on the y-axis, draw the graph of y = 2 sin x - cos 2x, for 0\u00b0 \u2264 x \u2264 180\u00b0.    (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given: y = 2sinx - cos2x  x0\u00b030\u00b060\u00b090\u00b0120\u00b0150\u00b0180\u00b0y-1.00.52.233.02.230.5-1.0  * When x = 0\u00b0  y = 2sin0 - cos2(0) = -1.0  * When  x = 60\u00b0  y = 2sin60\u00b0 - cos2(60\u00b0)  = 2( &radic;3&nbsp;/2 ) - cos120\u00b0  = 1.732 + 0.5 = 2.232  * When x = 90\u00b0  y = 2sin90\u00b0 - cos180\u00b0   = 2 - - 1 = 3  * When x = 120\u00b0  y = 2sin120\u00b0 - cos120\u00b0  =2(&radic;3&nbsp;2)+0.5= 1.732 + 0.5 = 2.23  * When x = 150\u00b0  y = 2sin150\u00b0 - cos300\u00b0  y=2(12)-0.5  y = 1 - 0.5 = 0.5","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>12>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Using the same axis, draw the graph of y = 1.25.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"From the graph, y = 1.25 as shown.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>12>c>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : GRAPHS OF SINE AND COSINE","question":"Use your graphs to find the values of x for which 2sinx - cos2x = 0.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"From the graph, values of x are x = 19.5\u00b0 or 159\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>12>c>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : GRAPHS OF SINE AND COSINE","question":"Use your graphs to find the roots of the equations  2sinx - cos2x = 1.25","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The roots are x = 42\u00b0 or x = 136.5\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>13>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES","question":"Two lines \u2220AB and CD intersect at X such that CAX is equal to BDX. If |AX| = 6cm, |XB| = 4cm and |CX| = 3cm, find |XD|.    (Leaving the answer in one decimal place b.c)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given that CA\u0302X = BD\u0302X,  thenAXBX=DXCX  6XD=34  64=XD3  XD=8cm","marks":"7","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>13>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"The diagram shows the positions of three points X, Y and Z on a horizontal plane. The bearing of Y from X is 312\u00b0 and that of Y from Z is 022\u00b0. If |XY| = 32 km and |ZY| = 50km, calculate, correct to one decimal place, |XZ|    (Leaving the answer in two decimal place ab.c)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"* Required to calculate |XZ|    Using Cosine rule, y2 = x2 + 22 - 2xzCosY  y2 = (50)2 + (32)2 - 2(50)(32)cos70\u00b0  y2 = (2500 + 1024) - (1094)  y2 = 2430  y = &radic;2430&nbsp; = 49.30km  \u2234 |XZ| = 49.30km","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>2006>SECTION II>13>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"The diagram shows the positions of three points X, Y and Z on a horizontal plane. The bearing of Y from X is 312\u00b0 and that of Y from Z is 022\u00b0. If |XY| = 32 km and |ZY| = 50km, calculate, correct to one decimal place, the bearing of Z from X.    (Leaving the answer in whole number format abc)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Using sine rule   xsinx=ysiny  50sinx=49.29sin70\u00b0  sinx=sin70\u00b0 \u00d7 5049.29  sinx=sin70\u00b0 \u00d7 5049.29\u00b0  sinx=50 \u00d7 0.939649.29=0.9531  sinx = 0.9531  x = sin-1(0.9531) = 72.39\u00b0  Therefore, the bearing of z from x = 312\u00b0 - 72.39\u00b0= 239.6\u00b0 = 240\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"}];